						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Hangin10 wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Leave Application.Run out as it's going to do its own message loop.</div><br />No, this is why you need to call Application.Run. Certain features depend on proper intialization as well as usage of the message loop.<br /><br />WedNESday, have you looked into using an idle loop? The Application.Idle event is fired each time the message queue is cleared, and seems to be the standard approach for WinForms XNA programs.<br /><br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">Public Class Form1<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; Private Sub Form1_Load(ByVal sender As System.Object, ByVal e As System.EventArgs) Handles MyBase.Load<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; AddHandler Application.Idle, AddressOf AppIdle<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; End Sub<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; Dim iteration As Integer<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; Sub AppIdle(ByVal sender As Object, ByVal e As EventArgs)<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 'Will cause form to paint, after which application will idle again.<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Invalidate()<br /><br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; ' Provide a visual cue that an idle has occurred<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Iteration += 1<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; Text = Iteration<br />&nbsp; &nbsp; End Sub <br />End Class<br /></div></div>

